## Conduction of Electricity and Flow of Charge

A simple circuit consists of a lamp connected to a battery.
![battery connected to lamp basic circuit.png](data:image/png;base64,)
In a circuit:

-   charge flows around the complete conducting path
-   the battery transfers energy to the charge and keeps it circulating round the circuit
-   the lamp transfers energy to the surroundings as heat and light

**Electric current** is a flow of electric charges. The lamp lights up because charged particles are moving through it. The charged particles move through _conductors_.

A copper wire consists of millions of copper atoms. Most of the electrons are held tightly to their atoms, but each copper atom has 1 or 2 electrons which are loosely held. Since these electrons are negatively charged, an atom that loses an electron is left with a positive charge and is called an **ion**.

The diagram shows that the copper wire is made up of a lattice of positive ions surrounded by _**free electrons**_. The ions can only vibrate about their fixed positions, but the electrons are free to move from one ion to another through the the lattice.

All metals have a structure like this:
![electric current lattice.png](data:image/png;base64,)

When a battery is attached to the copper wire, the free electrons are repelled by the negative terminal and attracted to the positive one. They still have a random movement but they now also all move slowly in the same direction through the the wire with a steady **[drift velocity](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5HFRs8X4gU0)**. ****Electrons in a circuit flow from negative to positive.

**Conductors and insulators**

Some materials are conductors, while others are insulators. This property is determined by the number of free electrons per m$^3$.
free electrons per m$^3$ $\propto$  conductivity

| type of material | number of free electrons per mm^3 | n, number of free electrons per m^3 |
| --- | --- | --- |
| conductor | ~ 1 * 10^20 | ~ 1 * 10^29 |
| semiconductor | ~ 1 * 10^10 | ~ 1 * 10^19 |
| insulator  | ~ 1 | ~1 * 10^9 |
### Electric currents

Current is measured in **Amperes (A)** using an ammeter. The ammeter is placed _in_ the circuit so that the electrons pass through it. The more electrons that pass through it in one second, the higher the current in amps. The position of an ammeter in a circuit does not matter; current is constant throughout a circuit.
![ammeter battery lamp circuit.png](data:image/png;base64,)

1 Ampere is a flow of about 1 $\times$ 10$^{18}$ electrons per second . The single electron is too small to be used as the basic unit of of charge, so instead a bigger unit is used, the **coulomb (C)**. The charge on one electron is 1.6 $\times$ 10$^{-19}$ C (1A = 1 C s$^{-1}$). You can picture a coulomb as a group of a large number of electrons. The more coulombs of charge that pass through an ammeter per second, the bigger the current.

$\text{current, }I = \frac{\text{charge, }Q}{\text{time, }t}$ or $I=\frac{Q}{t}$ so $Q = I\times t$

**1 coulomb is the amount of charge that passes a point when a current of 1 ampere flows for 1 second**, and **current is the rate of of flow of charge**.

If the current is changing with time, we think about a charge $\Delta$ _Q_ passing in a small time $\Delta$ _t_:

$I = \frac{\Delta Q}{\Delta t}$ or $\Delta Q=I\times\Delta t$

On a current-time graph, the area under the graph is equal to $\Delta$ _Q._
![current-time graph.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### Conduction in liquids and gases

A salt solution is an **electrolyte**; it can conduct electricity. In order to conduct, the liquid must contain charged particles that are free to move. Electrolytes contain both positive and negative ions. Positively charged ions in a solution are attracted to the negative terminal in a circuit while negatively charged ions are attracted to the positive terminal.

Under normal circumstances, air containts very few ions and so it does not conduct

![electrolytes.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### Current and drift velocity

The diagram shows part of a wire of cross-sectional area _**A**_ and length _**L**_ (area = _**A * L**_). If there are _**n**_ free electrons per m$^3$ of the wire , then the number of electrons in this section of the wire is _**n * A * L**_.

The charge on each electron is _**e**_, the total charge _**Q**_ on the free electrons is _**n A L e.**_

If it takes an electron a time _**t**_ to travel the length of the wire, after time _**t**_ all the electrons will have passed through the wire.

Since the current _**I**_ is the charge passing per second then: $I = \frac{\Delta Q}{\Delta t} = \frac{n A L e}{t}$, but $\frac{L}{T}$ is the average drift velocity so:
![drift velocity.png](data:image/png;base64,)
$$ I = n \;A\;v\;e $$

## Energy Transfer and Potential Difference

Electric current transfers energy from the battery to the lamp.

In the circuit, each electron gain electrical potential energy as it moves through the battery. Each electron then transports this energy to the lamp. As they move through the lamp filament, the electrons collide with the filament ions and so transfer energy to them. The ions vibrate more vigorously and the filament gets hot.

The energy transferred by a single electron is very small, so it is better to think of coulombs moving around the circuit. As each coulomb moves through the battery, it ‘picks up’ electrical potential energy. The coulomb ‘drops off’ this energy as it passed through the lamp and then returns to the battery to pick up more energy.

### Defining potential difference

The coulombs entering the lamp have electrical potential energy; those leaving have very little potential energy. There is a **potential difference (p.d.)** across the lamp. Because the potential energy of each coulomb has been transferred to heat and light within the lamp. P.d. is measured in **volts (V)** and is often called voltage.

_**The p.d. between two points is the electrical potential energy transferred to other forms, per coulomb of charge that passes between the two points.**_

The greater the p.d., the more energy transferred per coulomb. If a charge _Q_ transfers an energy _W_, then: $\text{p.d., }V=\frac{\text{energy transferred, }W}{\text{charge, }Q}$ or $V=\frac{W}{Q}$ or $W=QV$

_**If the p.d. is 1 volt, then 1 joule of electrical energy is transferred for each coulomb of charge.**_

Potential difference is measured using a voltmeter, placed _across_ the lamp. It measures the potential difference between coulombs entering the lamp and coulombs leaving the lamp.

If you were to set up another voltmeter along a section of the circuit, the p.d. would be near 0.
![measuring potential difference.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### Transferring energy

The p.d. across a car headlamp is 12V; when one 1 coulomb passes through the headlamp, 12J of energy is transferred to heat and light.

The p.d. across a table lamp is 230V; when one 1 coulomb passes through the headlamp, 230J of energy is transferred to heat and light.

We cannot say if the table lamp is brighter than the headlamp, because it depends on the time it takes for the energy to be transferred.

$\text{energy transferred, }W= \text{current, }I \;\times\;\text{time, }t\;\times\;\text{p.d., }V$

## Resistance and Resistivity

### Resistance

The greater the resistance of a component, the harder it is for charge to flow through it. Electrons make many collisions with tungsten ions as they move in the filament of a lamp, but they move more easily through copper wires because they make fewer collisions with the copper ions.

**How is resistance defined?**

If there is a p.d. across a conductor, a current goes through it. But when you apply the same p.d. across different conductors, the currents are different.

e.g.: A toaster and a kettle both have a p.d. of 230V, but the current is 10A in the kettle and 5A in toaster. The toaster has a higher resistance.

Resistance is measured in **ohms** ($\Omega$) and is defined as _**the ratio of the p.d. applied across a conductor to the current passing through it**._

![resistor basic.png](data:image/png;base64,)

$\text{resistance, }R=\frac{\text{p.d. across the the conductor, }V}{\text{current through the conductor, }I} \;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\text{or}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,R=\frac{V}{I}$

_**Resistors**_ are componenets that are made to have certain resistance. They can be made of a length of nichrome wire. The circuit symbol for a resistor is

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/6527286f-e602-4d77-b233-4c85c08f4fad/Untitled.png)

**Measuring resistance**

To find the resistance of a wire, you must place it in a circuit.
![resistor circuit.png](data:image/png;base64,)
The voltmeter tells you the the p.d. across the wire, and the ammeter tells you the current through it. Then you can calculate the resistance using the equation above. The table shows example readings you can get:

| V | I | R |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1.00 | 0.100 | 10.0 |
| 2.00 | 0.200 | 10.0 |
| 3.00 | 0.300 | 10.0 |

Materials that obey Ohm’s law are called **ohmic conductors**.

As the p.d. difference doubles, the current doubles. The resistance of the wire is constant because the ratio of _V_:_I_ is constant.

This is described by **Ohm’s law**:

**The current through a metal wire is directly proportional to the p.d. across it when the temperature is constant.**

### Resistivity

Not all metals are equally good conductors of electricity (e.g.: nichrome wires have much more resistance than copper wires). Certain factors affect the resistance of a wire:

-   Length — a long wire has more resistance than a short wire
-   Cross-sectional area — a thin wire has more resistance than a thick wire
-   Temperature — in _**metals**_, a hot wire has more resistance than a cold wire

The resistance of a wire at a constant temperature depends on its dimensions and on the material from which it is made. Every material has a property called its **resistivity**, $\rho$. It is measured in **ohm meters** ($\Omega \,\text{m}$).

Resistivity is defined as **numerically equal to the resistance of a sample of the material of unit length and cross-sectional area**.

| material  | type of material  | resistivity / ⁍ |
| --- | --- | --- |
| copper | conductor | 1.7 * 10^-8 |
| nichrome | conductor | 110 * 10^-8 |
| silicon | semi-conductor | 2.3 * 10^3 |
| glass | insulator | 1 * 10^12 |

If the resistivity, cross-sectional area and length of the material are known, the resistance can be calculated using the following equation:

$\text{resistance, }R =\frac{\text{resistivity, }\rho\;\times\;\text{length, }l}{\text{cross-sectional area, }A}$ or $R=\frac{\rho\;l}{A}$

The resistance of the wire is:

-   directly proportional to its length
-   inversely proportional to its cross-sectional area

## Current-Voltage Characteristics

The current in a metal wire is proportional to the p.d. across it. However, this property varies for other components of a circuit.

Current-voltage graphs can be used to see how current _I_ varies with voltage _V_ for any component _X_.

If _X_ is a resistor, the graph is a straight line passing through the origin, meaning that _I_ is directly proportional to _V_. Since $\frac{V}{I}$ is constant, the resistor has constant resistance.

![resistor vs filament lamp.png](data:image/png;base64,)

If _X_ is a filament lamp, the graph is a curve. Doubling the voltage produces less than double the current. The value of $\frac{V}{I}$ rises as the current increases. As the current increases, the metal filament gets hotter, and the resistance of the lamp rises.

The semi-conductor **diode** (device that allows current to flow in one direction only) behaves differently. There is almost _no_ current when the voltage is applied in the reverse direction. **The reverse diode has a very high resistance**.
![anode cathode symbol.png](data:image/png;base64,)
In the forward direction, the current increases very rapidly when the voltage rises above 0.6V. **The forward diode has a very low resistance**.

The LED behaves similarly to a diode, but emits light of a certain color as it conducts. The forward voltage needed to make an LED conduct is greater than 0.6V. Forward voltage needed varies with the color of the LED (e.g., it is higher for a blue LED than a red LED).



![current vs voltage in semiconductor diode.png](data:image/png;base64,)
*Graph for semiconductor diode*
_I-V graph for LED (light emitting diode)_

### The effect of temperature on resistance

All metals show an increase in resistance as their temperature rises. Metals contain large numbers of free electrons, and as they move through the metal lattice they collide with vibrating metal ions. The collisions oppose the flow of electrons and so the metal has resistance.

**Insulators and semi-conductors**

In insulators at room temperature, there are very few free electrons available for conduction. At high temperatures, some electrons have enough energy to ‘escape’ from their atoms and the insulator is able to conduct (to an extent). _**Resistance in insulators decreases as temperature increases**_.

Silicon is a very common semi-conductor. At low temperatures it is a poor conductor. As its temperature rises, more and more electrons break free from silicon atoms and so it becomes a better conductor. However, at about 150° breakdown occurs and the silicon is permanently damaged.

The resistance of many semi-conductors decreases as their temperature rises. These materials have a _**negative temperature coefficient**_ of resistance (NTC).
![thermistor vs metal wire resistance.png](data:image/png;base64,)
The **thermistor** (a type of resistor whose resistance is strongly dependent on temperature) is an important semi-conducting component. The resistance of an NTC thermistor is plotted against temperature (graph above).

**Superconductors**

When mercury is cooled down to 4.15 K ( -269 °C), it loses _all_ of its resistance and becomes a **superconductor**. Superconducting wires do not become hot because electrons can flow through them without any transfer of energy.

A material that can be superconductive needs to be cooled to below its _**transition temperature**_. For mercury that is 4.15 K.

### Electrical power

**Power** is measure in joules per second, called **watts** (W). The power of a device is the rate at which it transfers energy .

$\text{power, }P=\frac{\text{energy transferred, }W}{\text{time, }t}$ or $p=\frac{W}{t}$

We can also calculate power by combing the equation for power with the equation for energy ($W=I\,V\,t$):

$\text{power, }P= \text{current, }I\;\times\; \text{p.d., }V$ or $P=I\;\times\; V$

**Power and resistance**

For resistors and lamps, we can combine $P=I\;\times\; V$ with $V= I\;\times\;R$ to get 3 alternative equations for power:

$P=I\;\times\; V$ or $P=\frac{V^2}{R}$ or $P=I^2 \; \times\; R$

# 17: Electric Circuits

## Resistors in Series and Parallel

### The series circuit

If 2 ammeters are placed in a series circut at two different positions, they would both show the same reading.

Remember that current is the rate of flow of charge. All the electrons that go through one lamp must also go through the other lamp. No electrons are lost from the circuit, and so the number of coulombs passing any point each second must be the same.

_**In a series circuit, the current is the same at all points**

![series circuit.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### The parallel circuit

In a parallel circuit, the current splits between the two branches on the circuit.

As the electrons reach point A, some go into the top branch and some go into the bottom branch, until they reach point B.

_**In a parallel circuit, the current leaving and returning to the supply is the sum of the currents in the separate branches.**_
![parallel circuit.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### Kirchoff’s first law

In both circuits above, charge is _conserved_. In any circuit the cannot be created or destroyed, so when charge flows into a point it must flow out again. This law is usally expressed in terms of current: _**the sum of currents flowing into a point equals the sum of currents flowing out of that point**_. This law is useful when applied to branching circuits like the parallel circuit.

### Energy transfer in a series circuit

The two lamps in series have equal brighness, but each lamp is less bright than if it is connected to battery on it own.

You can see this by measuring the p.d. across both lamps and comparing it to the p.d. across each lamp separately.

_**In a series circuit, the total p.d. across all the lamps is the sum of the p.d.s across the separate lamps**_

![serial circuit 1.png](data:image/png;base64,)
![series circuit 2.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### Energy transfer in a parallel circuit

In a parallel circuit, each lamp is just as bright as if it were connected to the battery on its own.

You can see this by measuring the p.d. across each lamp separately and comparing it to the p.d. of the battery.

_**In a parallel circuit, the p.d. across each branch is the same**_.

Sometimes a combination of series and parallel circuits are used (e.g.: christmas lights, a few parallel rows of lamps connected in series).

![parallel voltage.png](data:image/png;base64,)
![parallel circuit 2.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### Resistors in series

For a series circuit:

-   the current through each resistor in series is the same
-   the total p.d. _V_ across the resistors is the sum of the p.d.s across the separate resistors ($V=V_1+V_2...)$
-   the combined resistance _R_ in the circuit is the sum of the separate resistors ($R=R_1+R_2...$)

![resistor in series.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### Resistors in parallel

For a parallel circuit:

-   the p.d. across each resistor in parallel is the same
-   the current in the main circuit is the sum of the currents in each of the parallel branches ($I=I_1+I_2...$)
-   the combined resistance _R_ is calculated using: $\frac{1}{R}=\frac{1}{R_1}+\frac{1}{R_2}...$
![parallel resistors.png](data:image/png;base64,)

## Potential divider and potentiometer

### The potential divider (voltage divider)

A **potential divider** is a circuit used when you want to use only part of the voltage provided by the battery/power source.
![voltage divider.png](data:image/png;base64,)
In the first diagram, the circuit has two resistors of 5$\Omega$, connected to a 12V battery . If two voltmeter are placed across each resistor, they would both read 6V each.

If one resistor is replaced with another that has a higher resistance, the 10$\Omega$ resistor would consist two-thirds of the total resistance in this circuit. So the p.d. across it would be 8V instead of 6V, while the other resistor’s voltmeter would read 4V.

The potential divider allows you to obtain an output voltage _V$_{out}$_ from a fixed voltage _V$_{in}$. V$_{in}$_ is the voltage across both of the resistors. _V$_{out}$_ is the voltage across the resistor _R$_2$._

You can apply the equation $V=I\times R$ to the resistors in this circuit.


$V_{out} = I\times R_2 \,\,\,\,\,\,\text{for the resistor that is being changed} \newline V_{in}= I\times (R_1+R_2)\,\,\,\,\,\, \text{for the resistance in series}$

Dividing the first equation by the second gives you:

$\frac{V_{out}}{V_{in}}=\frac{R_1}{R_1+R_2}$ or $V_{out}=V_{in}\times\frac{R_1}{R_1+R_2}$

**Using thermistors and LDRs in potential dividers**

Thermistors and light-dependent resistors can be used as sensors in electronic circuits. In this potential divider, one of the resistors is replaced by a **thermistor**.

This circuit has an output p.d. that changes with temperature. As the thermistor cools, its resistance rises. It takes a larger share of the input voltage, so _V$_{out}$_ rises. This circuit could be used to switch on a heater if _V$_{out}$_ rises above a certain value.
![thermistor as a potential divider.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### Variable resistors
![variable resistor.png](data:image/png;base64,)
Variable resistors can be used in two ways: to control the current, or to control the voltage. They consist of a resistance wire and a sliding contact. A variable resistor has 3 connections. Contacts 1 and 3 are fixed, and contact 2 is movable.

**The variable resistor as a rheostat**
![rheostat.png](data:image/png;base64,)
When a variable resistor is used to control current, it is called a **rheostat**. The rheostat only uses one of the two fixed contacts and the sliding contact.

As the slider S is moved, the length of resistance wire in the circuit is changed. The longer the wire, the higher the resistance, and so the smaller the current.
![variable resistor 2.png](data:image/png;base64,)
**The variable resistor as a potential divider**

The variable resistor can be used as a **potential divider** or **potentiometer** to control voltage.

This uses all 3 contacts on the variable resistor.

The supply _V$_{in}$_ is applied across the full length of the resistance wire AB. The sliding contact divides the resistor into two part, *R$_1$*and _R$_2$_.

If the slider _S_ is moved from _A_ towards _B_, _V$_{out}$_ is zero. If _S_ is at _A_, _V$_{out}$_ is the full input voltage of 6V. The rotary type of potentiometer is used in radios and other audio equipment as a volume control.

**Loading the potentiometer**
![potentiometer.png](data:image/png;base64,)
A potentiometer is _**loaded**_ when a resistor is connected to across its output terminals.

This lamp is in parallel with the resistor _R$_1$_. So, their combined resistance is less than _R$_1$_ alone. The bulb and _R$_1$_ together take a smaller share of the supply voltage and so _V$_{out}$_ is less.

## E.m.f. and Internal Resistance

### Electromotive force

Resistors and bulbs transfer electrical energy into other forms. This electrical energy is provided by a dry cell battery, a dynamo, or a solar cell for example.

A battery transfers chemical energy to electrical energy, so that as each coulomb moves through the battery it gains electrical potential energy. The greater the e.m.f. (in volts) of a source, the more energy is transferred per coulomb.

_**The e.m.f. of a source is the electrical potential energy transferred from other forms, per coulomb of charge that passes through the source**_.

If a charge _Q_ moves through a source of e.m.f. $\epsilon$, then:

$\text{energy transferred, }W=\text{charg, }Q\;\times\;\text{e.m.f., }\epsilon$ or $W=Q\;\epsilon$

**The internal resistance of a supply**

Suppose the dry cell in the diagram has an e.m.f. of 1.5V.

If the value of the resistance _R_ is reduced, the current in the circuit and p.d. across the resistor varies.
![internal resistance.png](data:image/png;base64,)

The table below shows some typical results.

| Value of R | Current I | P.d. across R |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 100 | 0.015 | 1.5 |
| 20 | 0.071 | 1.4 |
| 5.0 | 0.250 | 1.3 |
| 2.0 | 0.500 | 1.0  |

As the current in the circuit increases, the p.d. across the resistor falls.

The cell itself has some resistance, its _**internal resistance**_ (denoted by _**r**_). Each coulomb gains energy as it travels through the cell, but some of this energy is wasted or ‘lost’ as the coulombs move against the resistance of the cell itself. So the energy delivered by each coloumb is less than the energy supplied to it.

The internal resistance of most cells is often small enough to be ignored. Dry cells, however, have significant internal resistance, which is why they often become hot when supplying electric current.

## Kirchoff’s Second Law

Around any closed loop in a circuit, the sum of the e.m.f.s is equal to the sum of the p.d.s

### The circuit equation

**Terminal voltage** is thep.d. across the terminals of a cell (“battery”) in a circuit.

From Kirchoff’s second law, we know that energy in a circuit is conserved.

energy _**supplied**_ per coulomb from chemical energy of the cell =  energy _**delivered**_ per coulomb to the external circuit + energy _**wasted**_ per coulomb on the internal resistance.
or: e.m.f., ${\epsilon} = \text{terminal p.d}$, $V$ + lost volt, $v$


Current through resistors _R_ and _r_ is _I_. So, applying $\text{voltage = current }\times\;\text{resistance }$gives us

$\epsilon = V+I\,r$ or $\epsilon=I\,R+I\,r$ or $\epsilon= I(R+r)$

# 18: Magnetic Fields

## Magnetic Flux Density

### Magnetic fields

A **magnetic field** is a region where magnetic force can be felt.
![magnetic field.png](data:image/png;base64,)
To ‘see’ the shape of a magnetic field, you can place iron fillings around a magnet and they will align themselves along curved lines called **lines of flux**.

Lines of flux show both the direction and the strength of a magnetic field. From the lines you can see that the lines of flux always go from the N-pole to the S-pole.

The more closely packed the lines of flux, the stronger the magnetic field. The field is strongest nearest to the poles.

![magnetic lines 1.png](data:image/png;base64,)
![magnetic field 2.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### Magnetic flux density

The stronger a magnetic field, the more closely packed the lines of flux. The strength of a magnetic field is described by the **magnetic flux density**, _**B**_. It is the quantity of flux passing through a unit area at each point in the field. It is measured in _**tesla**_ (T).

B is a vector quantity because it has both sides and direction.

Manetic flux density can be measured using a Hall probe. A Hall probe can measure the magnetic flux density between the two poles of a horshoe magnet like in the diagram:

The probe must be held in the field so that the lines of flux pass at right angles through its tip. The meter connected to the probe gives a direct reading of the flux density in tesla.

![magnetic flux density.png](data:image/png;base64,)

**The Earth’s magnetic field**
![earth magnetic field.png](data:image/png;base64,)
A compass lines up in a north-south direction because the Earth has a magnetic field. The S-pole of the imaginary “magnet” inside the Earth is actually the northern hemisphere, and the N-pole is the southern hemisphere.

The lines of flux act at an angle to the Earth’s surface, except near the equator. This angle is called the **angle of dip**.

A compass needle held horizontally is only affected by the horizontal component of the magnetic flux.



## Coils, Solenoids, Electromagnets

### Magnetic effect of a current

An electric current is always surrounded by a magnetic field.

In a long, straight wire, like in the diagram, if you were to line up a card around the wire and sprinkle iron fillings, they would line up along the lines of flux.

You can place a compass on the card to find the direction of the magnetic field. With the current flowing up, the compass will point anti-clockwise. The magnetic field produced by an electric current is always oriented **perpendicular to the direction of the current flow**.

![magnetic effect of current.png](data:image/png;base64,)

The right-hand grip rule is helpful for remembering the directions of the magnetic field and the current.

The magnetic flux density of a wire is greatest close to the wire, and gets weaker as you move away from the wire.
![magnetic flux density 2.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### Magnetic field of a flat coil

The shape and direction of a magnetic field can be investigated similarly to those of a straight wire, with iron fillings and a compass.

Close to the wire, the lines of flux are circles, and run anti-clockwise around the left coil but clockwise around the right coil.

The fields to the sides of the coils are in the same direction, and combine to give a strong magnetic field.

![magnetic field on flat coil.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### Magnetic field of a solenoid

A **solenoid** is a long coil with a large number of turns of wire.

The magnetic field outside the solenoid, has the same shape as that of a bar magnet. Inside the solenoid, the lines of flux are close together, parallel and equally spaced. For most of the length of the solenoid, the magnetic flux density is constant. The field is uniform and strong.

The right-hand grip rule is also helpful here, but tilted perpendicularly: the thumb points towards the direction of the magnetic field while the curled fingers indicate the direction of current flow.

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/9274c8cf-3def-431d-a784-9fc41f145b42/Untitled.png)

### Magnetic materials

Magnetic fields can either be produced by permanent magnets or by electric currents.

The motion of each electron in an atom acts like a tiny current that generates its own tiny magnetic field. In some atoms the magnetic effects cancel out; in others they do not, so that each atoms acts like a tiny magnet.

In **ferromagnetic** materials, the tiny atomic magnets can line up with each other and produce a very strong magnetic field (e.g., iron, cobalt, nickel).

The magnetic field of a solenoid is greatly increased when a ferromagnetic core is placed inside the coil. That is because the atomic magnets of the core line up along the lines of flux inside the solenoid, and so the core becomes magnetized.

What happens when the current in the solenoid is turned off depends on the material of the core.

-   A _**steel**_ core stays magnetized. The tiny atomic magnets remain lined up, even when the external field is removed.
-   An _**iron**_ core quickly demagnetizes, because the atomic magnets have enough vibrational energy to turn in random directions.

A magnet that can be switched on and off is called an _**electromagnet**_.

### Measuring magnetic flux density

Magnetic flux density is a vector quantity; it has direction (shape) and magnitude. After magnetic field shapes, we need to discuss factors that affect its strength.

**The long straight wire**

The magnetic flux density of a long straight wire can be investigated using the following apparatus:

The lines of flux of a straight wire form circles around the wire, so the Hall probe has to be placed directly under the wire, so that it can be perpendicular to magnetic field.

This apparatus can be used to answer two questions:

-   when the probe is placed a fixed distance from the wire, how does _B_ vary as the current in the wire is increased?
-   when the current is kept constant, how does _B_ vary as the probe is moved away from the wire?

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/1bc6613d-873e-4b3f-8805-ea0aa706539a/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/69a5658c-4ec7-4e88-ba18-49421e06e408/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/4d666ad3-bb73-4866-b29f-974546aeb4d1/Untitled.png)

The two graphs show some typical results.

-   doubling the current doubles the flux density
-   doubling the distance from the wire halves the flux density

$$ \text{flux density, }B\,\text{(tesla)} \,\,\,\,\propto\,\,\,\,\frac{\text{current, }I\,\text{(amperes)}}{\text{distance, }r\,\text{(metres)}}\newline

$$

$$ \text{or} \,\,\,\,B=k\;\frac{I}{r} $$

_k_ is a constant that depends on the material around the wire. If the wire is in a vacuum, the equation is usually written as

$$ \text{flux density, }B=\frac{\mu_0\,I}{2\pi \, r} $$

where $\mu_0$ is a constant called the _permeability of free space_. The permeability $\mu$ of a material is a measure of its effect on the strength of the magnetic field. For a vacuum, $\mu_0$ = 4$\pi$$\times$10$^{-7}$ tesla metre ampere$^{-1}$(T m A$^{-1}$).

The wire in our circuit is in air, not a vacuum, so we use $\mu_{air}$ instead of $\mu_0$. Air, and most other materials, have almost the same permeability as a vacuum. But ferromagnetic materials have much higher permeabilities (e.g. $\mu_{iron}=8\pi\times10^{-4}$ T m A$^{-1}$).

**The solenoid**

A slinky can be used as an adjustable solenoid, as seen in the following circuit:

This apparatus can be used to answer three questions:

-   is _B_ uniform at all points inside the solenoids?
-   how does the value of _B_ at the centre of the solenoid vary as the current is increased?
-   how does the value of _B_ within the solenoid vary as the solenoid is stretched (so that _n_, the number of turns per metre, decreased)?

The two graphs show some typical results.

-   doubling the current doubles the flux density
-   doubling the number of turns per metre doubles the flux density

_B_ is uniform inside the solenoid, and:

$\text{magnetic flux density, }B\,\propto\,\text{turns per metre, }n\,\propto\,\text{current, }I$

When the solenoid is in a vacuum, (or in air), the equation can be written as:

$\text{magnetic flux density, }B = \mu_0\,\times\,n\,\times\,I$

## Magnetic Force on a Wire, Moving Charges

### Magnetic force

A wire carrying a current in a magnetic field will feel a force. A simple way to demonstrate this is with the following apparatus:

The two magnets are attached to an iron yoke with opposite poles facing each ither. The produce a strong, almost uniform field in the space between them.

When the current is switched on, the aluminium rod feels a force and moves along the copper rails. The current, magnetic field and the force are all _**at right angles**_ to each other.

If the direction of current flow _**or**_ the direction of the magnetic field is reversed, then the rod would move in the opposite direction.

The aluminium rod moves because the magnetic field of the permanent magnet interacts with the magnetic field of the current in the aluminium rod.

The following diagram shows the combined field of the magnet and the rod:

The lines of flux behave kind of like elastic bands, and it shows why the rod would be “catapulted” to the left.

**Fleming’s left-hand rule** can be used to predict the direction of the force.

### Factors affecting the size of magnetic force

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/9797cfc8-cf5c-45bd-ab49-3f5eb53b9552/Untitled.png)

In the apparatus shown, the balace is set to read zero after the manets have been placed on it. A current is then passed along the clamped aluminium rod.

Fleming’s left-hand rule shows that the force on the aluminium rod is actin upwards. If the magnets exert an upward force on the rod, then by Newton’s third law, the rod must be exerting an equal but opposite force on the magnets. This downwards force causes the readin on the scal to increase.

This setup can be used to show the following:

-   how the force varies when current is increased
-   how the length of the rod in the field affect the force
-   what happens to the force if the strength of the field is increased by adding more magnets to the yoke

The graphs show some typical results:

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/c8837d16-fb3a-4f4b-a44a-8ffd9db6ddf6/Untitled.png)

The diagrams show that the force _F_ on a conductor in a magnetic field is directly proportional to:

-   the magnetic flux density, _B_
-   the current, _I_
-   the length _l_ of the conductor in the field

$\text{force, }F=\text{flux density, }B\,\times\,\text{current, }I\,\times\,\text{length }l\text{ of wire}$ or $F=B\,I\,l$

This equation applies when the current is at 90$^\text{o}$ to the field.

When the angle $\theta$ is 90$^\text{o}$, the force has its maximum value. As $\theta$ is reduced the force becomes smaller. When the wire is parallel to the field, such as that $\theta$ is zero, the force is also zero.

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/05fb630b-3c17-46c4-be2c-fa7ea2222df6/Untitled.png)

If the current makes an angle $\theta$ to the magnetic field, then the force is given by

$F=B\,I\,l\,sin\theta$

The _size_ of the force depends on the angle the wire makes with the magnetic field, but the _direction_ doesn’t; the force is _**always at 90$^{\text{o}}$**_ to both the current and the field.

### Magnetic force on a moving charge

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/1c2277aa-29a4-4e48-9331-55f68371483b/Untitled.png)

The Northern Lights are caused by charged particles from outer space becoming trapped in the Earth’s magnetic field and spiral from one pole to the other. As they enter the atmosphere at the poles, they produce a glow in the sky.

This phenomenon occurs because a charged particle feels a force when it moves through a magnetic field. Factors that affect this force are:

-   the magnetic flux density, _B_
-   the charge on the particle, _Q_
-   the velocity of the particle, _v_

$\text{force, }F=\text{flux density, }B\,\times\,\text{charge, }Q\,\times\,\text{velocity, }v$ or $F=B\,Q\,v$

The force is always at 90$^{\text{o}}$ to both the current and the magnetic field, and its direction can be found using Fleming’s left-hand rule. A negative charge moving to the right has to be reated as a positive charge moving to the left.

If the charged particle is moving at an angle $\theta$ to the magnetic field, with a velocity _v_, then

$$ F=B\,Q\,v\,sin\theta $$

### Circular paths

The movement of charged particles is very important in atomic physics. In the “fine beam tube”, electrons move at right angles to a horizontal magnetic field. The path of the electron beam is shown by the blue circle.

What provides the centripetal force to make each electron move in a circular path?

In the second diagram, the electrons are moving in a uniform magnetic field. The flux density _B_ is _**into**_ the page (as shown by the X symbols). Each electron in the beam is moving with a speed _v_, at 90**°** to the field.

The field exerts a force _F_ on the electron, where _F = B Q v._ This force is always at 90**°** to the velocity. Because of this, the magnetic force changes the direction, but not the speed, of the electron. The _BQv_ force provides the centripetal force.

the equation for centripetal force is:

![23745D97-A084-4113-B645-B15D89DF4A5A.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/3e0f6d75-51ff-4614-8da8-6561c04f5034/23745D97-A084-4113-B645-B15D89DF4A5A.jpeg)

![F583A447-8F90-40D5-AEA4-9261AD953748.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/12b9c2ab-cfd1-4b9f-a73e-dc7e02223f16/F583A447-8F90-40D5-AEA4-9261AD953748.jpeg)

$$ F=\frac{m\,v^2}{r}\,\,\,\,\,\newline \text{where}\, m =\text{the mass of the particle and }r = \text{the radius of the circular path}  
$$

The centripetal force is provided by the magnetic force, so:

$$ \frac{m\,v^2}{r}=BQv $$

$$ \text{or, rearranging:} \,\,\,\,\,r=\frac{m\,v}{B\,Q} $$

From this we can see that the electrons move in a larger circle if their speed is increased, or if the magnetic force is made weaker.

To find the time period of 1 rotation:

$$ T=\frac{2\pi r}{v} \,\,\,\,\,\text{and }r=\frac{m\,v}{B\,Q}\,\,\,\text{can be combined:} \newline \newline T=\frac{2\pi}{v}\times\frac{m\,v}{B\,Q} = \frac{2\pi m}{B\, Q} $$

In a field of constant flux density _B_, the time period _T_ of the electron does not depend on its speed. A faster electron moves in a circle of a larger radius, but it takes exactly the same time for one revolution.

# 19: Electromagnetic Induction

## Magnetic Flux

### What is electromagnetic induction?

The diagram shows a copper rod connected to an ammeter. There is no battery in the circuit.

If you try to move the copper rod downwards, cut _**across**_ the horizontal magnetic field, the ammeter makes a brief ‘flick’ to the right, showing that a current has been **induced**.

If you move the rod upwards, the meter gives another flick to the left, showing that a current has been induced in the opposite direction.

![2B37F828-4095-4631-A53E-8DABD5A65718.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/ba024d21-0f94-462e-bf99-859d706a13be/2B37F828-4095-4631-A53E-8DABD5A65718.jpeg)

If you hold the rod stationary or move it along the field lines, there is no induced current.

### Why does electromagnetic induction occur?

When the copper rod is moved, its free electrons move with it. But when a charge moves in a magnetic field, it experiences a force on it (the _B Q v_ force). Fleming’s left-hand rule can be used to show that the the force on each electron is to the left, as shown in the diagram (an electron moving to the left has to be treated as a positive charge moving to the right).

So electrons accumulate at one end of the rod, making it negative. This leaves the other end short of electrons, making it positive. There is now a _**voltage**_ across the ends of the moving rod.

![4F1B388D-86A0-4645-9A76-5A65E1ACB3A7.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/9ebc8995-cd67-4cf0-9fd9-b46a767692e2/4F1B388D-86A0-4645-9A76-5A65E1ACB3A7.jpeg)

If the ends of the moving rod are joined to form a complete circuit, the induced voltage causes a current to flow round the circuit (which can be seen from the ammeter’s flicking).

This induced voltage is a source of electrical energy — an electromotive force (e.m.f.).

When a conductor is moving in a magnetic field like this, an e.m.f. is induced, even if there isn’t a complete circuit for current to flow.

### Faraday’s model of electromagnetic induction

The diagram shows another way to model electromagnetic induction:

When the bar magnet is passed through the coil, an e.m.f. is induced across the ends of the coil and the ammeter ‘flicks’. If the magnet is move _out_ of the coil, the ammeter ‘flicks’ the opposite way. If you move the coil instead of the magnet, a current is still induced. An e.m.f. is induced whenever there is _relative movement_ between the coil and magnet.

In this model (and the one in the previous section), the e.m.f. is induced by the metal rod/wire _cutting through_ the lines of flux.

This also works for a coil; as the magnet moves towards the coil, each turn of the coil cuts the lines of flux of the bar magnet.

![97C34813-B917-432D-908F-EA0D76C9FB41.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/8ae9314e-6a2e-489e-bd27-5b892ec38ebb/97C34813-B917-432D-908F-EA0D76C9FB41.jpeg)

The more turns on the coil, the greater the e.m.f. This is because _n_ turns will cut _n_ times more lines of flux than just one turn.

Another way Faraday’s flux model can be looked at is by used a yoke with magnets and a coil of wire called a search coil, connected to an ammeter.

If the coil is pulled out quickly, the ammeter ‘flicks’. In the diagram, 3 lines of flux pass through, or _**link**_, the coil. When it is out of the field, the flux linkage of the coil is zero. The **change in flux linkage** induces and e.m.f. across the coil.

So Faraday’s model tells us that an e.m.f. is induced when:

-   a conductor like the copper rod cuts through lines of flux
-   when there is a change in the flux linkage of a coil.

![BA26CC35-FC45-4370-B61F-84A2680ECC26.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/b39c7746-23c9-434d-9cab-5ab0655cc787/BA26CC35-FC45-4370-B61F-84A2680ECC26.jpeg)

You can increase the size of the e.m.f. induced across a coil by:

-   using a stronger magnet
-   using a coil with more turns of wire
-   using a coil with a greater cross-sectional area
-   moving the magnet faster

### Electromagnetic induction using two coils

Faraday was not using magnets when he discovered electromagnetic induction; he was using two coils, wrapped around an iron ring.

The diagram shows two coils placed side by side:

Coil C is connected to a battery and a switch.

Coil D is connected to a sensitive ammeter.

This setup can be used to answer the following questions:

-   What happens when the switch is closed?
    -   The meter flicks to the right and then goes back to zero
-   Why is a current induced in coil D?
    -   When the current is switched on, a magnetic field ‘grows’ around coil C. The growing flux lines link the turns of coil D. As its _**flux linkage**_ changes, an e.m.f. is induced across coil D and this induced e.m.f. drives a current through the ammeter.
-   Why does the ammeter reading go back to zero?
    -   When the current in coil C reaches its final steady value, the magnetic field around C is steady, so the flux linkage of D is _not changing_, and so there is no e.m.f. induced and current.

![EE66FEDE-17E2-40B6-AC24-217CFC1B8D05.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/7e57a851-db0d-4f5d-9fe2-9ae1bf865523/EE66FEDE-17E2-40B6-AC24-217CFC1B8D05.jpeg)

![C76AE912-9EF4-4711-A346-41419FF00319.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/4e89d46c-779d-49ba-95f5-d64122dc8cb0/C76AE912-9EF4-4711-A346-41419FF00319.jpeg)

-   what happens when the switch is opened?
    -   As the current in C falls, its magnetic field collapses. As the flux linkage of D changes, an e.m.f. is induced again. The meter flicks again, but this time to the left, because the induced e.m.f. and the current are in the opposite direction.

If the current in coil C is switched on and off repeatedly, the ammeter flicks to and fro as the current in coil D is constantly changing direction. This is called alternating current, or a.c.

If an a.c. is passed through coil C, the field around the coil will grow and decay in one direction, then grow and decay in the other direction. The magnetic flux linkage of of coil D will always be changing. Passing a.c. through coil C induces a.c. in coil D. Such an apparatus is called a simple **transformer**. Coil C is the primary coil and coil D is the secondary coil.

### Magnetic flux, ${\Phi}$

Lines of magnetic flux are drawn so that the density of the lines shows the strength of the field. So the number of lines passing at 90$^\text{o}$ through unit area represents the magnetic flux density _B_.

**Magnetic flux** has the symbol ${\Phi}$. It represents the _**total number**_ of lines of flux that ‘link’, or pass through at 90$^\text{o}$, a given area. Magnetic flux is measured in webers (Wb).

If _B_ is the flux per unit area, the total flux linking the area _A_ can be written as

$$ \text{magnetic flux, } \Phi=\text{magnetic flux density, }B\,\times \, \text{area, }A\,\,\,\,\text{or}\,\,\,\,\phi=BA $$

A coil of cross-sectional area _A_ and _N_ turns has a flux ${\Phi}$ _per coil linking it_, so:

$$ \text{total flux linkage, }\Phi=N\,\Phi\,= N\,BA\, $$

A _**change**_ in the flux linkage can happen for two reasons:

-   if a single turn coil of area _A_ is placed at 90$^\text{o}$ to a magnetic flux density that is changing then:

$$ \Delta\Phi=\Delta BA $$

-   if a single turn coil movies in a flux density _B_ so that the area linked by the flux changes, then:

$$ \Delta\Phi=B\Delta A $$

![BA3E6F28-BAFB-4853-A7CE-DEADB0471FF4.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/8821ce77-8090-455e-b37c-503226718ea7/BA3E6F28-BAFB-4853-A7CE-DEADB0471FF4.jpeg)

## Faraday’s Law & Lenz’s Law

### Fraday’s law

Faraday’s law makes the connection between the size of induced e.m.f. and the rate at which the flux is changing. It states that _**the magnitude of the induced e.m.f. is equal to the rate of change of the flux linkage**_.

$$ \text{induced e.m.f., }\epsilon=\frac{\text{change in flux linkage, }\Delta\Phi}{\text{time taken, }\Delta t} $$

For a coil with _N_ turns, the e.m.f. will be _N_ times as large:

$$ \epsilon=N\frac{\Delta\Phi}{\Delta t} $$

### Lenz’s Law

Lenz’s law tells us the direction of the induced e.m.f. It states _**the direction of the induced e.m.f. is such that it will try to oppose the change in flux that is producing it**_.

It can be understood using the following diagram:

As you move the N-pole into the coil, an e.m.f. is induced which drives a current round the circuit. Using the right-hand grip rule, you can show that the current produces a magnetic field with an N-pole at the end of the coil nearest to the magnet. So the coil _repels_ the incoming magnet, and in the way the induced current opposes the change in flux.

Following Lenz’s law, the current is reversed as the N-pole of the magnet is moves out, because the coil needs to _attract_ the receding N-pole.

![28502DD9-8D6A-4D72-B1BE-7A8BCDF2EFAB.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/52027594-92d8-4497-a222-9b8edef3d042/28502DD9-8D6A-4D72-B1BE-7A8BCDF2EFAB.jpeg)

Lenz’s law is a result of the conservation of energy. if you move the magnet into the coil, you feel the repulsive force. You have to do work to move the magnet against this force. This way, energy is transferred from the system moving the magnet to the electrical energy of the current.

Faraday’s law is often written with a negative symbol:

$$ \epsilon=N\frac{\Delta\Phi}{\Delta t} $$

it serves as a reminder that the _**e.m.f. is always induced in a direction so as to oppose the change in flux**_.

**Eddy currents**

When a piece of metal is moved in a magnetic field or placed in a changing magnetic field, currents, called **eddy currents**, are induced in the metal.

Eddy currents are always induced in a direction so as to oppose the motion or the change in flux producing them.

Eddy currents can be large, because the paths that they follow within the metal often have a very low resistance, causing the metal to become very hot.

![5627B161-B850-4CAC-BA36-DF72FBEFDD5A.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/ec1ebfb5-9447-4692-99ad-e494ed4b37b4/5627B161-B850-4CAC-BA36-DF72FBEFDD5A.jpeg)

**Magnetic braking**

The aluminium vane in the diagram, when moved between the poles of a horseshoe magnet, begins to oscillate but quickly stops.

As it swings, it cuts through the lines of flux of the magnet, so eddy currents are induced, which then produce their own magnetic field. This field interacts with the field of the magnet, and produces a force to oppose the motion of the metal (following Lenz’s law).

This effect is called **magnetic braking**.

![1D846E71-F999-4214-A16F-ABAF3AB2826A.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/52dac84e-796f-4b87-9bee-b4d6c32b8ff0/1D846E71-F999-4214-A16F-ABAF3AB2826A.jpeg)

# 21: Electric Fields

-   objects are usually uncharged and so are electrically neutral
-   objects can become charged by friction, when one material is rubbed against another material
-   a charged object can attract an uncharged object, such as small pieces of paper
-   electric charges can be positive or negative
-   a rubbed polythene strip gains a negative charge, a cellulose acetate strip gains a positive charge
-   like charges repel, opposite charges attract

## Electric Charge & Charging by Friction

### How do objects become electrically charged?

Normally, objects are uncharged because each atom has the same number of positive protons as negative electrons. Charging occurs when electrons are transferred from one material to another.

Friction can transfer electrons, such as when a polythene strip is rubbed with a cloth. The cloth loses electrons while the polythene strip gains electrons.

Polythene, like all insulating materials, has few free electrons. So the negative charge does not flow away from the rubbed region — it is a _**static charge**_. However, a conductor can only be charged if it is insulated from Earth (because charge could flow out of the object and into the Earth/other materials).

### Charging by electrostatic induction

A charged conductor will share its charge with an uncharged conductor that is placed in contact with it.

**Measuring charge**

One way to measure charge is using a **coulombmeter**. Some of the charge of the object is transferred to the coulombemeter when it is scraped across its metal cap. The coulombemeter then measures the charge placed on its cap. Reading can be positive or negative (indicating + or - charges).

### Forces between charges

Charges, whether attracting or repelling, exert a force on one another. The force _F_ between two charges is:

-   directly proportional to the charges Q1 and Q2
-   inversely proportional to the square of their separation _r_

The size of this force is given by _**Coulomb’s law**_:

$$ F= \frac{kQ_1Q_2}{r^2} $$

where:

$$ F\text{ is the force, in newtons}\newline Q_1\text{ and }Q_2\text{ are the charges, in coulombs}\newline r\text{ is the distance apart, in metres}\newline k\text{ is the constant of proportionality} $$

Coulomb’s equation strictly only applies only to point charges, but a sphere of charge behaves as if all its charge is behaves as if all its charge is concentrated at its centre (provided it is not placed too close to another charge).

**The value of the constant _k_**

When the charges are separated by a vacuum, the value of the constant _k_ is 9.0 $\times$ 10$^{9}$ $\text{N m}^2\;\text{C}^{-2}$. When they are separated by air, it is effectively the same.

This is the largest value that _k_ could have, because the size of the force is always reduced when an insulating material, other than air, is separating the charges.

In a vacuum (or air), the value of _k_ can be written as : $k= \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}$

where $\varepsilon_0$ is a constant called the the **permittivity of free space**. Its value is $8.85\,\times\,10^{-12}\text{ F m}^{-1}$ (the farad, F, is explained in a later chapter).

So $k= \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}=\frac{1}{4\times8.85\times10^{-12}\,\,\text{F m}^{-1}}=9.0\times10^9\text{ N m}^2\text{ C}^{-2}$

Every insulating material has a permittivity $\varepsilon$, which is greater than $\varepsilon_0$.

**Inverse-square law**

Coulomb’s law is also an inverse-square law and is very similar to Newton’s law of gravitation:

$F=\frac{k\,Q_1\,Q_2}{r^2}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,F=\frac{G\,m_1m_2}{r^2}$

## Electric Fields & Electric Potential

### Electric fields

An **electric field** is a region where a charge ‘feels’ a force. One way to see an electric field’s shape is using semolina grains sprinkled in castor oil.

Two electrodes in castor oil produce an electric field, and the semolina grains line up along the electric field lines.

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/9346ad6c-9474-4c09-9b8e-2ce3a9335169/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/3716537e-1823-4a44-ae48-9c3e60d045fc/Untitled.png)

### Electric field strength, _E_

Electric field _E_ strength is defined in a way similar to gravitiational field strength _g_.

_**The electric field strength at a point is the force per coulomb exerted on a positive charge placed at that point in the field**_.

A positive charge +_Q_ feels a force _F_ in the same direction as _E_. A negative charge -_Q_ feels a force _F_ in the opposit direction to _E_.

$\text{electric field strength, }E=\frac{\text{force, }F}{\text{charge, }Q}$ or $E = \frac{F}{Q}$, and $F=QE$

-   electric field strength _E_ is a vector quantity, the direction of the field is the direction of the force on a positive charge
-   the unit for _E_ is $\text{N C}^{-1}$, but an alternative unit is volts per metre ($\text{V m}^{-1}$)

**The uniform electric field**

In the diagram, there is a p.d. of about 1000 V across the parallel metal plates, so that they become charged:

A _**uniform**_ electric field is produced between the plates.

To make the field stronger, you can:

-   increase the p.d. across the plates
-   move the plates closer together

![829878B7-D6AF-4611-949A-9D86DE3BBB97.jpeg](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/63152236-804b-4020-8ba3-73262ad5de5f/829878B7-D6AF-4611-949A-9D86DE3BBB97.jpeg)

$$ \text{electric field strength, }E= \frac{\text{p.d. across the plates,}V}{separation of plates, }d $$

For electric field strength in a radial field, we combine coulomb’s law with the equation for electric field strength, to get an equation for the field strength _E_ at a distance _r_ away from a point charge +_Q_:

$$ E=\frac{k\,Q}{r^2} $$

### Electric potential

The **electric potential _V_** at any point in an electric field is the _**potential energy that each coulomb of positive charge would have if placed at that point in the field**_. Its unit is the joule per coulomb, or the **volt** (V). Gravitational potential is a scalar quantity.

**Potential difference**

The potential difference is is _**the energy transferred when one coulomb of charge passes from one point point to another**_.

$$ \text{energy transferred, }\Delta W=\text{charge, }Q\,\times\,\text{p.d., }\Delta V $$

**Equipotential surfaces**

All the points that have the _**same**_ potential in an electric field are said to lie an **equipotential** **surface.
